{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":566,"record_hash":"sha256:bc6bf7cf2e0f46caccb6b39d695be77a7bd160a64ec62b2ea19ef4b0a7a13099","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:46:30.615Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 56bceb\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1876\nOutput:\n# Agent Trail\n\nAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\nIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\nbehind a change.\n\n## Working Name\n\nUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n\nGood PR link text:\n\n- View Agent Trail\n- Explore Agent Trail\n- Agent Trail for this PR\n\nAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\nproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\nbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\nchange.\n\n## Product Shape\n\nFor v1, a reviewer starts from a GitHub pull request URL and opens the matching\nGitButler-owned Agent Trail URL by replacing the host. The server builds or\nloads a generated snapshot for that public pull request.\n\nExplicit PR description links, bot comments, check-run details links, or GitHub\napp panels can come later as distribution channels. They are not required for\nthe first build.\n\nThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\nrequest:\n\n- prompts and requests from the human\n- assistant responses and claims\n- tool calls and tool results\n- tests and validation attempts\n- decisions and tradeoffs\n- follow-up questions\n- edge cases discussed or missed\n\nThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\ntruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\nunderstand the change.\n\n## Core Question\n\nAgent Trail should answer:\n\n> What agent context